</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010190-0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 156171 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 1, 1990, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part E; Page 6; Column 1; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
449 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: TEACH YOUNGSTERS TO PROFIT FROM SETBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: How can I help build my children's self-esteem and make them 
able to succeed in a tough world? I don't want them to be insensitive, but I 
don't want them to wilt every time something difficult comes along. My wife and 
I aren't wealthy, so they're going to have to make it on their own. -- T.S. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR T.S.: The fact that you're aware that youngsters need to be able to cope 
with frustration and disappointment is already a plus. Children need to learn 
how to cope with defeat and parents need to explain that we all learn from our 
failures. If a child doesn't know this, he may limit himself by trying only 
those tasks he knows he can do well. 
</P>
<P>
When things go wrong, when your youngster gets a disappointing grade or when he 
fails on a test, help him not to be overcome by these setbacks. Remind him that 
they are temporary and that he can learn from his past errors and do better 
next time. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Scheier, a psychologist at Carnegie-Mellon University, found that 
optimists handle stress better than pessimists. Optimists tend to respond to 
disappointments by formulating a plan of action and asking other people for 
help and advice while pessimists are likely to react to the same difficulties 
by trying to forget the whole thing or by assuming there's nothing they can do 
to change things. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: I'm engaged to a wonderful woman but I'm troubled by what 
happens to her when she drinks. First of all, she doesn't seem to know when to 
stop, and when I mention this the next day, she gets defensive, assuring me 
that she can stop whenever she wants. I know that after we've been celebrating 
at a party, she doesn't remember things that have happened the night before. 
This is important because she frequently behaves badly. How can I handle this 
and should I insist that she go on the wagon? -- F.T. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR F.T.: I doubt that you'd accomplish much if you simply "insisted" that she 
go on the wagon. She's showing symptoms of alcoholism, such as personality 
changes when she drinks, denial about her drinking patterns and blackouts or 
memory lapses. While some non-alcoholics do occasionally experience these same 
symptoms, it's unusual and is a strong indication that there are serious 
drinking problems. 
</P>
<P>
There are ways to spot future alcoholics, such as the need to find constant 
excuses for a drink, and the pattern of having every occasion -- sad or happy 
-- begin and end with a drink. Another clue that you seem to be getting is the 
inability of your friend to stop drinking or to refuse alcohol once she's 
started. 
</P>
<P>
Try to get her to some meetings of Alcoholics Anonymous. If she refuses, I'd 
postpone plans for marriage until she reconsiders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
