<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOTORCYCLE THEFT SUSPECT WOUNDED BY LA MESA POLICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A La Mesa police officer shot a man in the chest Friday night while police were 
attempting to arrest him in Lemon Grove. 
</P>
<P>
The victim, identified as James L. Warnicke, 22, of Lemon Grove was listed in 
serious condition Sunday at UC San Diego Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
La Mesa police spokeswoman Allison Moore said Officer Jeff Allen followed two 
motorcyclists to a Lemon Grove liquor store. 
</P>
<P>
Waiting outside, Allen was advised by his radio dispatcher that one of the 
motorcycles had been reported stolen. The officer asked for backup assistance 
and when other officers arrived, they confronted the two men. 
</P>
<P>
Moore said that the officers asked both men to raise their hands, but that 
Warnicke "suddenly moved his hands to an object in his waistband." She said the 
officers again ordered him to stop, but that Warnicke repeated the movement and 
that Allen then fired one shot, hitting Warnicke in the right side of the 
chest. 
</P>
<P>
Warnicke was taken by Life-flight to the medical center, where he was held on 
suspicion of motorcycle theft. 
</P>
<P>
His companion, Andre Perez, 26, of La Mesa, was held in the downtown county 
jail on suspicion of possessing a dangerous weapon and on several outstanding 
warrants. 
</P>
<P>
Moore said detectives found a knife at the scene, but she said it was unclear 
what, if anything, Warnicke may have had inside his waistband. 
</P>
<P>
Allen, a 3-year police veteran, was placed on administrative leave while the 
investigation is continuing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010289-0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 573 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 2, 1989, Monday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
