<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRAIL OF AGELESS ART IS NOGUCHI LEGACY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM WILSON, Times Art Critic 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A biological theory known as hybrid vigor holds that a child born of parents of 
different races will possess greater intelligence and physical health than 
either of them. Metaphorically, at least, the productive and long-lived 
sculptor Isamu Noguchi with his Japanese-poet father and Caucasian-American 
mother seemed animated by this force. Born in Los Angeles in 1904 under the 
sign of Scorpio, he died last Friday in New York at 84. 
</P>
<P>
It came as something of a surprise to realize that when Noguchi's ledger was 
closed he had left a protean legacy of artworks scattered across three 
continents and had attained the status of the modern art world's leading 
sculptural patriarch. And not just because he had outlived the competition. The 
quality of his work had never faltered into commercial decoration or 
self-caricature as it has with so many long-lived modern masters. There was an 
incredible steadiness about Noguchi's work, as if it were produced by someone 
-- or something -- ageless, like a mountain stream patiently sculpting its 
rocks. Noguchi's career added up to a fairly vivid endorsement of 
miscegenation. 
</P>
<P>
Hiroshima mon amour. 
</P>
<P>
There is a socio-psychological theory which holds that people born of mixed 
race will be more troubled than their parents, suffering feelings of not quite 
belonging anywhere and never being exactly sure of who they are. Some evidence 
suggests that Noguchi sensed himself as this Marginal Man. Little of the 
autobiographical turns up in accounts of his career. He was married once, 
briefly. He moved about somewhat restlessly, widening his geographical circuit 
until in recent years he divided his time between homes in New York, Japan's 
Shikoko Island and junkets to other countries to work on an ever-expanding 
roster of commissions. He liked Pietrasanta, Italy, and recently caught a cold 
there, which eventually led to his death. 
</P>
<P>
If Noguchi felt displaced, he certainly identified with both poles of his 
alienation. During the Japanese-American internment of World War II, he 
voluntarily had himself confined to one of the camps. It was a wonderfully 
subtle affirmation of his roots and a truly aristocratic gesture of contempt 
toward the American establishment. After that he always looked a bit like a 
prisoner, keeping the top button of his shirt closed without wearing a tie. He 
looked at once like a convict, a Zen priest and a Eurasian polo fancier played 
by Toshiro Mifune. 
</P>
<P>
For many of the decades he was around one was barely aware of him. His image 
lacked the dramatic presence of the volcanic Picasso, the bear-like charm of 
David Smith or the trendiness and wit of Claes Oldenburg. Noguchi was like a 
shadow cast on the floor through the light from an open door, enigmatic and 
without substance. 
</P>
<P>
What was he up to? 
</P>
<P>
In 1978, Minneapolis' Walker Art Center organized an exhibition whose travels 
brought it to the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art. For many adults it was 
the first opportunity to have a focused look at a possibly minor artist from, 
when was it exactly, the '20s or '40s or sometime and is he still alive? 
</P>
<P>
The show was an authentic revelation. Noguchi had studied with the great 
Brancusi but by the '40s, he was making works like "Avatar," whose forms 
resembled the biomorphic surrealism of Miro while retaining the sensuous 
material elegance of Brancusi. Noguchi seemed to be moving like a vacuum-fish, 
absorbing everything in his wake. In the early '60s, he made forms like 
unshelled snails before anyone heard of Funk. 
</P>
<P>
And so it went. Long before Robert Rauschenberg collaborated with Merce 
Cunningham, Noguchi did sets for Martha Graham's dances, for "Appalachian 
Spring" and "Frontier." They had the skeletal spareness of Giacometti's "The 
Palace at 3 A.M." Decades before art developed a social conscience or an 
awareness that real light and space were sculptural materials, Noguchi designed 
playgrounds. When artists furniture was not even a glimmer in the aesthetic 
eye, Noguchi made lamps. 
</P>
<P>
The years rolled on and Noguchi began to receive larger and more prominent 
commissions. They made it clear that his originality consisted less of pure 
invention and more of hybrid vigor. Squint at a sunken garden at Yale's 
Beinecke Library and it is clearly a minimalist paraphrase of Japanese Zen 
gardens with their raked sand and huge boulders. 
</P>
<P>
Noguchi's work tells us that the individualism and inventiveness of the 
Occident was anticipated in the collectivism and tradition of the Orient, where 
nature itself is regarded as a huge artwork. The artist does not dictate to 
nature. He listens to it and does its bidding. Just set the boulder on edge, 
give it a few taps and it is a sculpture. And we thought it was so 
revolutionary when Duchamp told us the art is found rather than made. 
</P>
<P>
Noguchi came to Los Angeles to work on his plaza for the Japanese American 
Cultural and Community Center and his spectacularly calm "California Scenario" 
in Costa Mesa's South Coast Plaza. He did not think highly of his hometown and 
was not a pleasant man to meet. He answered questions with contemptuous 
casualness and seemed to wish to be elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
He came across as a man so aware of his absolute aloneness that the only way to 
survive was to convince himself he had chosen it out of obligation to a greater 
mission. 
</P>
<P>
If one is going to fuse oneself with nature -- to take on the personality of 
the relentless wind or the tireless stream -- it requires a certain 
ruthlessness, an austere humility that can play out as arrogance. 
</P>
<P>
What does it mean that Noguchi made the monomaniacal gesture of establishing a 
museum to himself but then placed it in an obscure section of Long Island City, 
N.Y.? 
</P>
<P>
Noguchi set himself the superhuman task of fusing time and space into an art 
that makes Stonehenge modern and subsumes the idea of modernism to man's most 
primitive impulses, delivering him back -- truly civilized -- to the endless 
cycled rhythms of nature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Sculptures in Noguchi garden in Costa Mesa blend with mirrored buildings 
to create an eerie scene. MARK BOSTER / Los Angeles Times; Photo, Artist Isamu 
Noguchi in 1983, displaying sculpture he designed for Japanese American 
Cultural and Community Center. JAYNE KAMIN-ONCEA / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
