<HEADLINE>
<P>
IF THE COLLAPSE OF MARRIAGE IS NOBODY'S 'FAULT,' WHY DO WOMEN PAY?; 
</P>
<P>
LAW: TWENTY YEARS AGO, CALIFORNIA MOVED TO MAKE DIVORCE RATIONAL, EVEN 
CIVILIZED. ENTER THE HORROR STORIES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLEN GOODMAN, Ellen Goodman writes a syndicated column in Boston. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the very end of "The War of the Roses," Danny de Vito delivers the moral to 
his cautionary tale about the mutually assured destruction of a marriage. 
"Civilized divorce," he concludes, "is a contradiction in terms." 
</P>
<P>
This is more than a punch line to the movie. It may serve as the footnote to 
that product of wishful thinking and right-minded reform that marks its 20th 
anniversary this week: no-fault divorce. 
</P>
<P>
In January, 1970, the state of California put into effect a kind of peace 
treaty. No-fault divorce was to end the use of the courtroom as a battleground 
between divorcing parties. 
</P>
<P>
Until that moment, divorce in America was for the most part awarded only after 
one party was proved to be guilty for ending the marriage. This was a messy and 
often deceitful process to prove that one person was at fault, guilty of 
adultery or cruelty, and that there were "grounds" for divorce. 
</P>
<P>
In a legislative sweep of the hand, California eliminated fault as the grounds 
for divorce, or for awarding alimony, or for dividing property, which was to be 
split equally. The law, signed by then-Gov. Ronald Reagan, was hailed as the 
first step to making divorce rational, equitable, modern, quick and, yes, 
civilized. 
</P>
<P>
Where California led, the country followed. In relatively rapid order, no-fault 
divorce became common in every state. And so, too, more slowly, did the horror 
stories. 
</P>
<P>
Judith Wallerstein, the author of "Second Chances," says now from the vantage 
point of two decades, "How little we anticipated what the results might be. We 
passed legislation without a sufficient attempt to foresee the consequences." 
</P>
<P>
What were the consequences? No-fault divorce did make the legal process less 
scandalous. But the new law and the loss of the old bargaining chip, fault, 
contributed to an economic disaster. 
</P>
<P>
Lenore Weitzman's seminal book, "The Divorce Revolution," was the first to 
document the real-life effect of the law in California. "No fault was taken to 
mean no responsibility," says Weitzman, now a sociology professor at Harvard. 
The results were "a systematic impoverishment of women and children." 
</P>
<P>
In the early flush of feminism, the law presumed and the judges rigorously, 
even ruthlessly, implemented the idea that women should be able to support 
themselves, even if they'd been out of the work force for years. The strict 
equal treatment of economic unequals was financially disastrous. 
</P>
<P>
Alimony or spousal support diminished in amount and length. Ordered to divide 
property equally, couples had to sell homes, taking children away from their 
old neighborhoods and schools. There was no allowance made for the one real 
economic asset of a modern marriage: present and future earning power. 
</P>
<P>
"No-fault was the vehicle or the excuse for saying that what happened in the 
past didn't matter, what matters is that you divide up the property and each go 
your own way, "says Weitzman. " Judges used it to cut women off." 
</P>
<P>
To this day, economists argue about how much no-fault divorce added to the 
plight of women and children. But they all agree it was a factor. Today, 
nationally, five years after divorce, a woman's income is still 30% of what it 
was during the marriage. A man's income is 14% more. 
</P>
<P>
Now there is a movement to reform the reform. The movement says that no fault 
is not the same as no responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
Once again California has been among the first to experiment. It has, among 
other things, revised the standards for spousal support and the duration of 
that support. Equally important, it is changing judicial attitudes about 
property division that forced the sale of children's homes. 
</P>
<P>
Across the country, the second wave is pointed not only at a more viable 
spousal support, but also at enforcing child-support decrees. There is heated 
discussion as well about whether business assets and professional credentials 
should be considered "marital property" upon divorce. 
</P>
<P>
But this reform wave, like the last one, takes place in a larger context. Today 
most families need two incomes. When one family becomes two single households, 
there is rarely enough. 
</P>
<P>
Moreover, for all the rhetoric and real change, most women still enter marriage 
earning less. They often go on earning less throughout marriage and especially 
motherhood. And so they leave a marriage earning less. 
</P>
<P>
There are limits to how much any divorce law can make up for the inequities of 
a whole society. The old reforms continued and even exaggerated those 
inequities. All these reforms can try to do, as Weitzman puts it, is to see at 
least that husband and wife "both share the burdens of divorce in America." 
</P>
<P>
So a truce signed 20 years ago with high ideals about marital peace and 
domestic justice and gender equality has come up against economic reality and 
more than a touch of emotional cynicism. It just may be that a civilized 
divorce law is also a contradiction in terms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010290-0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 156372 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 2, 1990, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 7; Column 1; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
791 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
JUSTICE FOR NORIEGA ISN'T IN THE CARDS; 
</P>
<P>
LAW: OLLIE NORTH'S CLOAK OF DISPENSATIONS WOULD FIT THE GENERAL JUST AS WELL. 
THE GOVERNMENT CAN'T AFFORD TO TRY HIM -- OR TO LET HIM FREE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALAN M. DERSHOWITZ, Alan M. Dershowitz is a professor of law at Harvard 
University and writes a syndicated column. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The one country we can be certain Manuel Noriega will not ask to be sent to is 
Romania. The new revolutionary government's concept of justice -- secret 
"trial," no appeal, quick execution -- is unlikely to appeal to Noriega's sense 
of survival. 
</P>
<P>
Like many tyrants of the past, Noriega will be seeking a peaceful and luxurious 
retirement. And if history is a guide to the future, he will find some fellow 
dictator willing to extend him a professional courtesy. Among the modern 
precedents is the hospitality extended to mass murderer Idi Amin by Saudi 
Arabia, and the welcome mat rolled out for Nazi war criminals by Paraguay and 
Syria. Even civilized countries like the United States and France have given 
sanctuary to despots -- like the Shah of Iran, Ferdinand Marcos and Jean-Claude 
"Baby Doc" Duvalier, wanted for trial in their own countries. 
</P>
<P>
Administration sources, pointing to Noriega's indictment on drug charges, have 
tried to distinguish the case by arguing that he is "a common criminal." But 
the Shah, Marcos and Duvalier were also regarded as criminals by their own 
people. 
</P>
<P>
The fact that we sent in the U.S. Army to capture Noriega weakens our claim 
that he is a "common criminal" as distinguished from a political opponent. He 
may well be both. The U.S. government certainly did not regard him as a common 
criminal when our CIA worked hand-in-hand with him over a considerable number 
of years. We treated him as the powerful political figure he was. He may have 
been an s.o.b., but as Franklin Roosevelt once said of another U.S.-supported 
Central American dictator: "At least he's our s.o.b." 
</P>
<P>
Manuel Noriega is no longer our s.o.b., but he apparently knows a lot about 
other s.o.b.'s with whom we are, and have been, dealing. He also knows about 
our CIA operations throughout Central and South America. It is for this reason 
that knowledgeable sources are doubting that President Bush really wants him to 
be tried in an American court. Under the rules of evidence, Noriega's lawyers 
could demand disclosure of highly embarrassing government files. If our 
intelligence services refuse to produce those files, the charges against 
Noriega might have to be dropped, as several charges were dropped against 
Oliver North, John Poindexter and others. 
</P>
<P>
The difference is that the Bush Administration and the Central Intelligence 
Agency wanted the charges dropped against North and Poindexter. They used the 
cloak of national security as an excuse for helping their friends. Noriega is 
nobody's friend. The last thing the Administration wants now is a trial in an 
American court that results in a dismissal of charges against him. Our legal 
system is based on precedents. The crowning irony would be for the precedent 
established in the case of hero Ollie North to be used to free villain Manuel 
Noriega. 
</P>
<P>
There were many officials in Washington who were hoping that Noriega would 
suffer the fate of Nicolae Ceausescu, the Romanian dictator executed by his own 
army, or of Jose Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, the Medellin drug boss killed in a 
shootout. 
</P>
<P>
Short of Noriega being killed, the next best outcome for the Administration may 
well be the one that is currently playing itself out. The problem is now 
squarely in the hands of the Vatican. No one expects us to use gunboat 
diplomacy on the nunciature. Our hands are tied. We did the best we could. Or 
did we? Is it possible that Noriega's all-too-obvious Vatican option did not 
occur to a single Washington official? Could we not have surrounded the 
nunciature to prevent Noriega from sneaking in? Or did we really close our eyes 
to this possibility? 
</P>
<P>
It's not too late to get our hands on the fugitive who has continued to make a 
fool of us. We can simply wait him out. Although international law may forbid 
us from physically entering the nunciature and grabbing Noriega, he remains 
subject to capture as soon as he tries to leave. Cars, helicopters and 
airplanes -- even those bearing the seal of the Vatican -- are not the 
"territory" of the Vatican as the nunciature is. If the Vatican were to decide 
to allow Noriega to seek asylum in Cuba or some other country, we need not 
allow him safe passage. 
</P>
<P>
Remember that not so long ago, we forcibly stopped an Egyptian aircraft 
carrying terrorists and made it land in Italy, where the terrorists were 
apprehended. We could do the same with Noriega. But there are many who believe 
that we will not do everything in our legal, diplomatic and military power to 
see to it that Noriega is brought to trial in a America. courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
As a Noriega lawyer put it to me: "They know that the case of the United States 
vs. Manuel Noriega would really turn out to be the case of Manuel Noriega vs. 
the CIA, Ronald Reagan and George Bush." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Boerger / The Daily Yomiuri, Tokyo 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
