<HEADLINE>
<P>
PACIFIC STORM BRINGS AREA CHANCE OF RAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A small Pacific storm will bring cloudy skies and a 50% chance of showers to 
Orange County today, but provide little relief from the drought, the National 
Weather Service predicted Monday. 
</P>
<P>
"There is a small system moving through. However, it is not going to give us 
what we need," a weather service spokesman said. "This certainly won't affect 
the drought. We could catch up later this year, you never know." 
</P>
<P>
The front moving through Southern California this morning could bring a 
quarter-inch of rain along the coast and one-half to three-fourths of an inch 
in the mountain areas. Snow is predicted above 5,000 feet. 
</P>
<P>
As the front moves east into the deserts, forecasters say, the chance of 
showers will diminish from 50% to 30%, leaving partly cloudy skies tonight. 
Clear, cool and windy weather is expected Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Lows will be in the upper 40s except for some inland valleys, which could get 
temperatures as low as 35. Highs will be in the low 60s. Winds up to 15 m.p.h. 
will come out of the south and shift to west-to-northwest with velocities of 20 
to 30 m.p.h. by this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
Nationally, a low-pressure system stretched along the East Coast from Canada 
through New York, New Jersey, eastern Pennsylvania and Maryland into Virginia, 
bringing rain and raising temperatures into the 40s and 50s. Intermittent rain 
and fog clouded parts of the Washington area. 
</P>
<P>
Light snow and freezing rain made end-of-the-holiday traveling hazardous in the 
Great Lakes region, the upper Ohio Valley and parts of the northern Atlantic 
coast. 
</P>
<P>
A cold front brought rain to much of the South, where temperatures were 
generally mild. Meanwhile, a dry air mass covering much of New Mexico, 
Oklahoma, Texas, Arkansas and Louisiana drove temperatures down overnight 
Sunday and early Monday, to the teens in the Texas Panhandle and the 40s in the 
Rio Grande Valley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
